import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
"37": {
"1": "<p>When Hezekiah heard it, he tore his clothes and covered himself with sackcloth and went into the house of the LORD. The covenant king's response to maximum crisis: mourning and prayer in the temple. Christ in Gethsemane (Matt 26:36-46) follows this exact pattern — going to the place of prayer in anguish, submitting to the Father. Hezekiah going to the house of YHWH models the access to the Father that Christ opens for all: Hebrews 4:16 — <em>let us then with confidence draw near to the throne of grace, that we may receive mercy and find grace to help in time of need.</em> The torn clothes of grief become the robe of righteousness that Christ bestows on his people (Isa 61:10).</p>",
"2": "<p>And he sent Eliakim, who was over the household, and Shebna the secretary, and the senior priests, covered with sackcloth, to the prophet Isaiah. The king turns to the prophet as the channel of YHWH's word — recognizing that human strategy is exhausted and the decisive resource is the divine word. Christ is himself the Word (John 1:1) and the Prophet greater than Moses (Deut 18:15; Acts 3:22). Every NT instruction to pray in Christ's name (John 14:13-14) is the fulfillment of Hezekiah's sending to Isaiah: seeking the word of God through the mediator in the hour of crisis.</p>",
"3": "<p>They said to him, Thus says Hezekiah: This day is a day of distress, of rebuke, and of disgrace; children have come to the point of birth, and there is no strength to bring them forth. The birth-pangs metaphor for the predicament of maximum crisis without resolution — labor without delivery. Jesus uses this identical image for the end-time distress (Matt 24:8: <em>all these are the beginning of birth pains</em>). Paul: <em>the whole creation has been groaning as in the pains of childbirth right up to the present time</em> (Rom 8:22). The crisis that has brought labor but not delivery is the human predicament that Christ resolves: the resurrection is the delivery, the birth into new creation that all the suffering was laboring toward.</p>",
"4": "<p>It may be that the LORD your God heard all the words of the Rabshakeh, whom his master the king of Assyria has sent to mock the living God, and will rebuke the words that the LORD your God has heard. Therefore lift up your prayer for the remnant that is left. The prayer is for the remnant — the preserved covenant community. <em>The living God</em> is the key theological distinction: the nations' gods are silent because they are dead; YHWH hears because he lives. Hebrews 9:14: <em>how much more will the blood of Christ... purify our conscience to serve the living God.</em> 1 Timothy 4:10: God is <em>the Savior of all people, especially of those who believe.</em> The remnant for whom Hezekiah prays is the seed of the church gathered by Christ.</p>",
"5": "<p>When the servants of King Hezekiah came to Isaiah, Isaiah said to them: Say to your master this: The answer comes through the prophet to the king's messengers — YHWH responds to covenant prayer through his word. This pattern of prayer followed by prophetic response is fulfilled in Christ who is both the one prayed to and the one through whom the answer comes. John 16:23-24: <em>whatever you ask of the Father in my name, he will give it to you.</em> The chain — king prays, prophet speaks, YHWH acts — is compressed in Christ into the single mediator (1 Tim 2:5) who is simultaneously priest, prophet, and king.</p>",
"6": "<p>Thus says the LORD: Do not be afraid because of the words that you have heard, with which the servants of the king of Assyria have reviled me. Do not be afraid — the most frequent divine command in Scripture, appearing here at the moment of maximum military threat. The risen Christ's first words in almost every resurrection appearance are <em>do not be afraid</em> (Matt 28:10; Rev 1:17). The same divine word that addresses Hezekiah's crisis addresses the terrified disciples after the crucifixion. John 16:33: <em>In the world you will have tribulation. But take heart; I have overcome the world.</em></p>",
"7": "<p>Behold, I will put a spirit in him, so that he shall hear a rumor and return to his own land, and I will make him fall by the sword in his own land. YHWH's method of defeating the empire: not a counter-army but a spirit — an internal disposition that redirects the enemy from within. This is the pattern of Christ's defeat of the powers: Colossians 2:15 — he <em>disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, triumphing over them in him.</em> The cross appears as the empire's victory; it is YHWH's infiltration of the enemy's own system to bring about his defeat. The same power that reversed Sennacherib's plans reversed the plans of sin and death at the resurrection.</p>",
"8": "<p>The Rabshakeh returned, and found the king of Assyria fighting against Libnah, for he had heard that the king had departed from Lachish. The enemy's attention diverts precisely when YHWH's word says it will — the sovereign orchestration of geopolitical events that appear as coincidence. Proverbs 21:1: <em>the king's heart is a stream of water in the hand of the LORD; he turns it wherever he will.</em> The timing of Jesus's arrest, trial, and crucifixion is similarly governed: <em>my hour has not yet come</em> (John 2:4) — until it has, and then it proceeds on the Father's schedule, not Rome's or the Sanhedrin's.</p>",
"9": "<p>When he heard concerning Tirhakah king of Cush, He has set out to fight against you, he sent messengers again to Hezekiah. The rumor about Tirhakah (Ethiopian pharaoh) threatening Sennacherib's rear — the geopolitical pressure that YHWH orchestrates as his instrument. Acts 4:27-28: <em>both Herod and Pontius Pilate, with the Gentiles and the peoples of Israel, gathered together to do whatever your hand and your plan had predestined to take place.</em> Every seemingly independent historical actor who converges on the crucifixion — Judas, Pilate, the chief priests, the Roman soldiers — is the divine orchestration behind the second threat-letter, serving YHWH's ultimate purpose.</p>",
"10": "<p>Do not let your God in whom you trust deceive you by saying, Jerusalem will not be given into the hand of the king of Assyria. The attack now comes in writing — a letter designed to undermine faith in YHWH's promise. This is the temptation-pattern: <em>did God really say?</em> (Gen 3:1) transferred to the written divine promise. Hezekiah spreads the letter before YHWH (v14); Jesus in the temptations responds to every Satanic assault with <em>it is written</em> (Matt 4:4, 7, 10). Both the prayer-response and the Scripture-response are the model for the covenant community's posture under attack on YHWH's reliability.</p>",
"11": "<p>Behold, you have heard what the kings of Assyria have done to all lands, devoting them to destruction. And shall you be delivered? The comparative argument: look at every other nation — they all fell. 1 Corinthians 1:26-29: God chose the weak, the foolish, the despised — things that are not — to bring to nothing things that are, so that no human being might boast. The world-empire's track record of destroying everyone is exactly the evidence against which the resurrection of Christ stands as the definitive exception. YHWH delivers what no human strategy can protect, through the one whom death could not hold (Acts 2:24).</p>",
"12": "<p>Have the gods of the nations delivered them, the nations that my fathers destroyed, Gozan, Haran, Rezeph, and the people of Eden who were in Telassar? The roll-call of defeated nations whose gods failed them. Paul at Athens (Acts 17:30-31): God commands all people to repent because he has given proof — <em>by raising him from the dead</em> — that Jesus is the appointed judge of the world. The resurrection is YHWH's definitive answer to the comparative-religion challenge: no other god has raised his representative from the dead on the third day in fulfillment of Scripture. The list of failed gods ends with the risen Christ.</p>",
"13": "<p>Where is the king of Hamath, the king of Arpad, the king of the city of Sepharvaim, the king of Hena, or the king of Ivvah? The vanished kings — all the human powers reduced to rhetorical questions. Revelation 19:19-21: the kings of the earth who gathered to make war against Christ and his people are defeated and captured. The enumeration of destroyed kings that the Rabshakeh offers as evidence of YHWH's powerlessness becomes, in Revelation, the evidence of Christ's universal victory. Every power that opposes the covenant community ends as a rhetorical question.</p>",
"14": "<p>Hezekiah received the letter from the hand of the messengers and read it; and Hezekiah went up to the house of the LORD and spread it before the LORD. Spreading the threatening letter before YHWH — taking the enemy's words directly to God in prayer. This is the model of intercessory prayer: bringing the specific attack on God's honor and his people's safety into the divine presence and waiting for YHWH's response. Hebrews 7:25: Christ <em>always lives to make intercession</em> for those who draw near to God through him. The High Priest takes every threat, every accusation, every letter from the enemy into the throne room of the Father.</p>",
"15": "<p>And Hezekiah prayed to the LORD. The simple act of prayer — the covenant king addresses YHWH. The entirety of Jewish and Christian prayer-theology flows from this act. Jesus teaches his disciples to pray (Matt 6:9-13) in the same covenant-address pattern. His own high priestly prayer (John 17) is the fulfillment and completion of what Hezekiah begins: the king-priest in the temple, addressing the Father on behalf of his people, seeking the Father's glory and the people's protection.</p>",
"16": "<p>O LORD of hosts, God of Israel, enthroned above the cherubim, you are the God, you alone, of all the kingdoms of the earth; you have made heaven and earth. The address: YHWH alone is God of all kingdoms, creator of heaven and earth. John 1:1-3: <em>in the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God... all things were made through him, and without him was not anything made.</em> Colossians 1:16: <em>all things were created through him and for him.</em> The God enthroned above the cherubim, sole creator of all — this is the one who became flesh in Jesus of Nazareth (John 1:14).</p>",
"17": "<p>Incline your ear, O LORD, and hear; open your eyes, O LORD, and see; and hear all the words of Sennacherib, which he has sent to mock the living God. The prayer for YHWH to hear and see — and the identification of Sennacherib's taunt as directed against the living God. Jesus prays before Lazarus's tomb: <em>Father, I thank you that you have heard me. I knew that you always hear me</em> (John 11:41-42). The confidence that the Father hears is the ground of all prayer in Christ's name. The blasphemy against the living God that Hezekiah asks YHWH to hear and judge is the same blasphemy that confronts Christ on the cross (Matt 27:39-43: the mocking of the crucified), which the Father answers at the resurrection.</p>",
"18": "<p>Truly, O LORD, the kings of Assyria have laid waste all the nations and their lands. The honest acknowledgment of the enemy's real power — not minimizing what faces the covenant community. The pattern of honest confession before petition: Romans 3:23 acknowledges the universal human predicament (all have sinned) before announcing the solution (3:24: justified freely by his grace). Prayer that names reality accurately — the enemy IS powerful; the situation IS desperate — is the prayer that receives YHWH's answer. The Psalms of lament follow this pattern, and Jesus prays them on the cross (Ps 22:1: <em>my God, my God, why have you forsaken me</em>).</p>",
"19": "<p>And have cast their gods into the fire. For they were no gods, but the work of men's hands, wood and stone. Therefore they were destroyed. The theological diagnosis: the nations fell not because YHWH is weak but because their gods were not gods. 1 Corinthians 8:4-6: <em>there is no God but one... for us there is one God, the Father... and one Lord, Jesus Christ, through whom all things came and through whom we live.</em> Paul's argument completes Hezekiah's prayer: the one God whom Sennacherib lumped with the wood-and-stone gods is the God who raised Jesus. The resurrection distinguishes YHWH from every non-god definitively.</p>",
"20": "<p>So now, O LORD our God, save us from his hand, so that all the kingdoms of the earth may know that you alone are the LORD. The petition's ultimate purpose: the salvation of the covenant community so that all kingdoms know YHWH alone. Psalm 67:2: <em>that your way may be known on earth, your saving power among all nations.</em> Acts 4:12: <em>there is salvation in no one else, for there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved.</em> The salvation of Jerusalem from Sennacherib is the type of the salvation accomplished at Jerusalem through Christ's cross and resurrection — the act by which all kingdoms of the earth are summoned to know YHWH.</p>",
"21": "<p>Then Isaiah the son of Amoz sent to Hezekiah, saying, Thus says the LORD, the God of Israel: Because you have prayed to me concerning Sennacherib king of Assyria... The prophetic answer is explicitly linked to the prayer: <em>because you have prayed.</em> The connection between prayer and prophetic response models the NT pattern: <em>you do not have, because you do not ask</em> (James 4:2). The prayer that is answered is the prayer offered through the mediator. Christ's role as mediator means that every prayer offered in his name reaches the Father precisely as Hezekiah's prayer reached YHWH — and the answer comes through the living Word who is both prophet and king.</p>",
"22": "<p>This is the word that the LORD has spoken concerning him: She despises you, she scorns you — the virgin daughter of Zion; she wags her head behind you — the daughter of Jerusalem. The daughter of Zion's defiant contempt for the empire — the covenant community that refuses to yield. Revelation 12:1-2 presents the woman clothed with the sun (the covenant community bearing the Messianic child) who cannot be destroyed despite the dragon's total assault. The virgin daughter who scorns the empire's power is the type of the church that stands — not by military strength but by the victory of the Lamb (Rev 12:11).</p>",
"23": "<p>Whom have you mocked and reviled? Against whom have you raised your voice and lifted your eyes to the heights? Against the Holy One of Israel! The climactic identification: the blasphemy was against the Holy One of Israel — who is identified in the NT as Jesus (Mark 1:24; John 6:69: <em>we have believed and have come to know that you are the Holy One of God</em>). Every taunt directed at Jerusalem, every mockery of covenant faith, is directed against the one who is the Holy One. The cross is where this blasphemy reaches its peak (Matt 27:39-44) and where YHWH's answer — the resurrection — is most powerfully given.</p>",
"24": "<p>By your servants you have mocked the LORD, and you have said, With my many chariots I have gone up the heights of the mountains, to the far recesses of Lebanon. The pride-speech: the military-logistical boast. James 4:13-16: <em>you who say, today or tomorrow we will go into such and such a town... you boast in your arrogance. All such boasting is evil.</em> The precise pattern of Sennacherib's boast — cataloguing military strength as evidence of autonomy from God — is the pride that the incarnation dismantles. Philippians 2:3-8: Christ did not consider equality with God something to be grasped but emptied himself. The cross is the anti-Sennacherib: the one who possessed all divine power becoming the slave, crucified.</p>",
"25": "<p>I dug wells and drank waters, and I dried up with the sole of my foot all the streams of Egypt. The claims of self-sufficient resource extraction — I found water, I diverted rivers. This is the boast of the one who thinks he is not dependent on YHWH's provision. Jesus in John 4:13-14 offers the living water that no human digging can access: <em>everyone who drinks of this water will be thirsty again, but whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again.</em> The water the emperor boasts of extracting by his own foot is the counterpart to the water that flows from Christ's side (John 19:34) and from the throne of God and the Lamb (Rev 22:1).</p>",
"26": "<p>Have you not heard that I determined it long ago? I planned from days of old what now I bring to pass, that you should make fortified cities crash into heaps of ruins. YHWH's declaration of pre-determined sovereignty — Sennacherib's success was YHWH's own decreed plan all along. Ephesians 1:11: <em>in him we have obtained an inheritance, having been predestined according to the purpose of him who works all things according to the counsel of his will.</em> Acts 2:23: the crucifixion happened <em>according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God.</em> YHWH's pre-determined plan encompasses the use of empire for covenant purposes — and ultimately the cross is the supreme expression of what was planned from days of old.</p>",
"27": "<p>Their inhabitants, shorn of strength, are dismayed and confounded, and have become like plants of the field and like tender grass, like grass on the housetops, blighted before it is standing. All humanity's strength is grass before YHWH's sovereignty. 1 Peter 1:24-25: <em>All flesh is like grass and all its glory like the flower of grass. The grass withers, and the flower falls, but the word of the Lord remains forever. And this word is the good news that was preached to you.</em> Peter quotes Isaiah 40 to show that the word of the gospel — the word that announces Christ's resurrection — is the one thing that stands when all human strength withers. The empire's subjects are grass; the risen Christ is the eternal Word.</p>",
"28": "<p>I know your sitting down and your going out and coming in, and your raging against me. YHWH's total knowledge of Sennacherib — every movement, every word, every attitude. Psalm 139:2-4: <em>you know when I sit and when I rise... Before a word is on my tongue you, LORD, know it completely.</em> Jesus embodies this divine omniscience: John 2:25 — <em>he knew what was in a man;</em> John 21:17 — <em>Lord, you know everything; you know that I love you.</em> Hebrews 4:13: <em>no creature is hidden from his sight, but all are naked and exposed to the eyes of him to whom we must give account.</em></p>",
"29": "<p>Because you have raged against me and your complacency has come to my ears, I will put my hook in your nose and my bit in your mouth, and I will turn you back on the way by which you came. YHWH redirects the empire through its own nostrils — the divine control exercised from within. Colossians 2:15: Christ <em>disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, triumphing over them in him.</em> The cross is the hook in the nose of sin, death, and Satan: what appeared to be the powers' triumph is actually YHWH's turning them back on the way by which they came. The empty tomb is the evidence that the empire has been redirected.</p>",
"30": "<p>And this shall be the sign for you: this year eat what grows of itself, and in the second year what springs from that. Then in the third year sow and reap, and plant vineyards, and eat their fruit. The three-year recovery pattern as sign — the third year of full agricultural restoration. The three-day pattern of the Passion resonates: the sign of Jonah (Matt 12:39-40: three days and nights in the earth) is the definitive sign. John 12:24: <em>unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit.</em> The agricultural restoration on the third year is the pattern of the resurrection-harvest: the death-winter of the cross gives way to the spring of new creation.</p>",
"31": "<p>And the surviving remnant of the house of Judah shall again take root downward and bear fruit upward. The surviving remnant taking root and bearing upward fruit — Isaiah 11:1 (the shoot from the stump of Jesse who bears the Spirit's fruit). Romans 11:16: <em>if the root is holy, so are the branches.</em> John 15:5: <em>I am the vine; you are the branches. Whoever abides in me and I in him, he it is that bears much fruit, for apart from me you can do nothing.</em> The remnant that takes root in the Messiah is the church — and its upward fruit-bearing is the Spirit's work in the community that abides in Christ.</p>",
"32": "<p>For out of Jerusalem shall go a remnant, and out of Mount Zion a band of survivors. The zeal of the LORD of hosts will accomplish this. The band going out from Zion — Acts 1:8: <em>you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem, in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth.</em> The apostolic mission is the band of survivors going out from Mount Zion, empowered not by human zeal but by the zeal of YHWH of hosts — the Spirit poured out at Pentecost (Acts 2). The same phrase <em>the zeal of the LORD of hosts will accomplish this</em> closes the Immanuel-child prophecy (Isa 9:7), linking this remnant-mission to the Messianic child of whom the whole chapter speaks.</p>",
"33": "<p>Therefore thus says the LORD concerning the king of Assyria: He shall not come into this city or shoot an arrow there, or come before it with a shield or cast up a siege mound against it. The absolute protection of the city — no arrow, no shield, no mound. Matthew 16:18: <em>on this rock I will build my church, and the gates of Hades will not prevail against it.</em> The city Christ protects is the new covenant community — no power can breach it with arrow or siege. Revelation 21:27: <em>nothing unclean will ever enter it, nor anyone who does what is detestable or false, but only those who are written in the Lamb's book of life.</em></p>",
"34": "<p>By the way that he came, by the same he shall return, and he shall not come into this city, declares the LORD. YHWH's sovereign reversal of the empire's trajectory — sent back the way it came. This is the final word to every power that opposes the covenant community: you will not enter, you will return. Acts 12:23: Herod, who had accepted divine worship and struck down James, was struck by an angel and died — sent back by YHWH, not by human counter-force. The powers that oppose Christ's church are consistently redirected without achieving their goal.</p>",
"35": "<p>For I will defend this city to save it, for my own sake and for the sake of my servant David. YHWH defends the city for two reasons: his own sake (his honor among the nations) and for David's sake (his covenant oath). Hebrews 7:22: <em>Jesus has become the guarantee of a better covenant.</em> The Davidic covenant that grounds the city's protection finds its ultimate fulfillment in the Son of David (Matt 1:1) who is the reason YHWH defends his covenant people. Every defense of the church is ultimately <em>for the sake of my servant Jesus</em> — in whom all the covenant promises of David are Yes and Amen (2 Cor 1:20).</p>",
"36": "<p>And the angel of the LORD went out and struck down 185,000 in the camp of the Assyrians. And when people arose early in the morning, behold, these were all dead bodies. The overnight destruction of the Assyrian army by a single angel — the definitive divine rescue without human military action. This is YHWH's answer to every <em>has any god delivered his land?</em> question (36:18). Colossians 2:15: on the cross Christ <em>disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, triumphing over them in him.</em> The single angelic act that destroys 185,000 overnight is the type of the cross-and-resurrection — the solitary act of the Son of Man that disarms every power arrayed against the covenant community.</p>",
"37": "<p>Then Sennacherib king of Assyria departed and went home and lived at Nineveh. The empire that came against YHWH's city is simply gone — not destroyed in battle but dismissed by the divine word. 2 Corinthians 2:14: <em>thanks be to God, who in Christ always leads us in triumphal procession.</em> The retreat of the world-empire having accomplished nothing against the covenant city is the pattern of every power that confronts the gospel-community and finds it cannot be overcome (Acts 5:39: if this is of God, you cannot overthrow it). The Assyrian departure without firing a single arrow (v33) is the pattern of the cross's victory: the enemy leaves because the battle was already won on ground he could not see.</p>",
"38": "<p>And as he was worshiping in the house of Nisroch his god, Adrammelech and Sharezer, his sons, struck him down with the sword and escaped into the land of Ararat. And Esarhaddon his son reigned in his place. Sennacherib killed by his own sons while worshiping his god — the final irony of the chapter. The man who mocked YHWH's ability to protect his city is killed in his own sacred space by those closest to him. The structure echoes the betrayal pattern: Christ too was handed over by one of the twelve, in the context of a sacred meal. Yet where Sennacherib's death is pure tragedy, Christ's death is the atoning sacrifice that achieves what the cross cannot be accused of being — defeat. The one betrayed rises; the one who struck down Sennacherib simply flees. Isaiah 37 ends with the empire's self-destruction; the gospel ends with the resurrection of the one the empire destroyed.</p>"
}
}

data = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'isaiah')
merge_comm(data, NEW)
save_comm('mkt-christ', 'isaiah', data)
print('Done.')
